Brief notes

An appendix to my book on musical modes and scales: a complete list of all 2,048 modes of all 205 scales in twelve-tone equal temperament, the primary tuning system used in Western music. The links to each scale go to Ian Ring’s page, an invaluable resource for scale analysis.

Key to scale identifiers

I list three forms of identification for each scale:

  1. CID (“Carnatic ID”) uses a numbering system inspired by South India’s Carnatic Numbered Melakarta, where the more front-loaded a scale’s intervals are, the earlier it appears in the numbering.
  2. RID (“Ring ID”) is derived from a binary representation of which tones are present in a scale. It is so named because it is the numbering system Ring uses on his site.
  3. IID (“Interval ID”) represents the intervals in the scale (in semitones). It is a hexadecimal representation, so A = 10, B = 11, and C = 12.

Key to interval inversions

Each interval of n semitones can be considered the inversion of the interval of 12 - n semitones. That is, moving up by a perfect fourth and moving down by a perfect fifth land on the same note, just at a different octave. The table above lists interval inversions on the same row.

Interval inversion key
IntervalInversion
Minor secondMajor seventh
Major secondMinor seventh
Minor thirdMajor sixth
Major thirdMinor sixth
Perfect fourthPerfect fifth
Augmented fourthDiminished fifth
I consider the augmented fourth and diminished fifth to be inversions of each other because they are semantically different in music theory contexts: the augmented fourth is the result of raising the fourth degree of the scale, while the diminished fifth is the result of lowering the fifth degree of the scale. This can depend on several factors. For instance, in the C major scale:
  • Traveling from F up to B is considered an augmented fourth, since F is only note where traveling three notes up the major scale does not result in a perfect fourth.
  • Traveling from F down to B is considered a diminished fifth, since F is the only note where traveling four notes down the major scale does not result in a perfect fifth.
